'''Bradley "Brad" Marshall''' is an American [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] politician and the former [[chief financial officer]] (CFO) of the [[Democratic National Committee]] (DNC).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/08/02/democratic-national-committee-ceo-amy-dacey-resigns-in-wake-of-email-breach/|title=Top Democratic National Committee officials resign in wake of email breach|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> In 2016, he gained notoriety after [[WikiLeaks]] published an email in which he questioned the faith of the [[Jewish]] candidate for the democratic nomination, [[Bernie Sanders]].<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2016/07/22/new-leak-top-dnc-official-wanted-to-use-bernie-sanderss-religious-beliefs-against-him/ |title=New Leak: Top DNC Official Wanted to Use Bernie Sandersâ€™s Religious Beliefs Against Him |website=Theintercept.com |date= |accessdate=2016-07-24}}</ref> He wrote: "It might may [sic] no difference, but for KY and WVA can we get someone to ask his belief. Does he believe in a God. [sic] He had skated on saying he has a Jewish heritage. I think I read he is an atheist. This could make several points difference with my peeps. My Southern Baptist peeps would draw a big difference between a Jew and an atheist."<ref name="auto1">{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/dnc-emails/emailid/7643 |title=Search the DNC email database |publisher=[[WikiLeaks]] |date= |accessdate=2016-07-24}}</ref><ref name="auto2">{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/the_slatest/2016/07/22/email_indicates_dnc_wanted_bernie_sanders_asked_about_god.html|title=Leaked Email Indicates DNC Wanted Bernie Sanders Interrogated About His Faith|first=Jeremy|last=Stahl|date=22 July 2016|publisher=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate blog]]|accessdate=2 August 2016|via=Slate}}</ref><ref name="auto3">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jul/27/dnc-email-leak-bernie-sanders-jewish-democrats|title=Jewish Democrats express doubts that US is ready for atheist president|first=David|last=Smith|date=27 July 2016|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2 August 2016|via=The Guardian}}</ref><ref name="auto4">{{cite web|url=http://hotair.com/archives/2016/07/23/dnc-ceo-on-suggested-attack-on-sanders-religion-amen/|title=DNC CEO on suggested attack on Sanders’ religious belief: "AMEN" - Hot Air|date=23 July 2016|publisher=[[Hot Air]]|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Marshall earned a bachelor's degree in [[accounting]] from [[Morehead State University]] in [[Morehead, Kentucky]].<ref name="p2016.org"/>
==Career== Since 1992, Marshall was CFO of the DNC.<ref name="p2016.org">{{cite web|url=http://www.p2016.org/parties/dnc13.html|title=Democratic National Committee (DNC) Organization 2013-14, Democracy in Action|website=p2016.org|accessdate=2 August 2016|quote=Chief Financial Officer Brad Marshall CFO at the DNC since 1992. Previously he worked for a decade as a CPA in Lexington, KY, 1982-92. Financial vice president and controller for Melco Construction in London, KY, 1980-82. Senior manager at PriceWaterhouseCoopers in Lexington, 1978-80. Staff accountant at Deloitte & Touche in Lexington, 1976-78. Bachelor's degree in accounting from Morehead State University in Morehead, KY.}}</ref> He resigned in August 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/08/dnc-ceo-resigns-amid-turmoil-226570|title=DNC CEO resigns amid turmoil|publisher=[[Politico]]|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://talkingpointsmemo.com/livewire/amy-dacey-luis-miranda-brad-marshall-leave-dnc|title=3 Top Staffers Out At DNC In Wake Of Wasserman Schultz’s Resignation|publisher=[[Talking Points Memo]]|accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> From 1982 to 1992, he was a [[certified public accountant]] (CPA) in [[Lexington, Kentucky]].<ref name="p2016.org"/> From 1980 to 1982, he was financial vice president and controller for [[Melco Construction]] in [[London, Kentucky]].<ref name="p2016.org"/> From 1978 to 1980, Marshall was senior manager at [[PriceWaterhouseCoopers]] in Lexington, Kentucky and from 1976 to 1978, he was staff accountant at [[Deloitte & Touche]], also in Lexington.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.p2016.org/parties/dnc15.html|title=Democratic National Committee (DNC) Organization 2015, Democracy in Action|publisher=p2016.org|accessdate=2 August 2016|quote=Chief Financial Officer Brad Marshall CFO at the DNC since 1992. Previously he worked for a decade as a CPA in Lexington, KY, 1982-92. Financial vice president and controller for Melco Construction in London, KY, 1980-82. Senior manager at PriceWaterhouseCoopers in Lexington, 1978-80. Staff accountant at Deloitte & Touche in Lexington, 1976-78. Bachelor's degree in accounting from Morehead State University in Morehead, KY.}}</ref>
===DNC WikiLeaks scandal=== {{main article|2016 Democratic National Committee email leak}}
In 2016, Marshall gained notoriety after WikiLeaks published an email in which he questioned the faith of the [[Jewish]] candidate for the Democratic nomination, [[Bernie Sanders]].<ref name="auto"/> He wrote: "It might may [sic] no difference, but for KY and WVA can we get someone to ask his belief. Does he believe in a God. [sic] He had skated on saying he has a Jewish heritage. I think I read he is an atheist. This could make several points difference with my peeps. My Southern Baptist peeps would draw a big difference between a Jew and an atheist."<ref name="auto1"/><ref name="auto2"/><ref name="auto3"/><ref name="auto4"/> He followed up the initial email with another stating, "It's these Jesus thing."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/dnc-emails/emailid/11454 |title=Search the DNC email database |publisher=[[WikiLeaks]] |date= |accessdate=2016-07-24}}</ref> Days after the leak, Marshall confirmed the authenticity of the emails in posting an apology<ref>{{cite web|last=Scher |first=Bill |url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/07/top-dnc-staffer-apologizes-for-email-on-sanders-religion-226072#ixzz4FGyq4G1a |title=Top DNC staffer apologizes for email on Sanders’ religion |website=Politico.com |date=1998-07-24 |accessdate=2016-07-24}}</ref> to his Facebook profile that read, "I deeply regret that my insensitive, emotional emails would cause embarrassment to the DNC, the Chairwoman, and all of the staffers who worked hard to make the primary a fair and open process. The comments expressed do not reflect my beliefs nor do they reflect the beliefs of the DNC and its employees. I apologize to those I offended."
