'''David Morrow''' (December 18, 1960 – February 1, 2010)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://businessjournalism.org/2010/02/02/reynolds-chair-dave-morrow-dead-at-49/ |title=Dave Morrow, Reynolds chair, former editor of TheStreet.com, dead at 49 : BusinessJournalism.org Reynolds Center for Business Journalism |publisher=Businessjournalism.org |date=2010-02-02 |accessdate=2011-12-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224124111/http://businessjournalism.org/2010/02/02/reynolds-chair-dave-morrow-dead-at-49/ |archivedate=2012-02-24 |df= }}</ref> became [[editor-in-chief]] of [[TheStreet.com]] in July 2001. Under his tenure, TheStreet.com won numerous journalism awards, including the prestigious [[Gerald Loeb Award]] in 2005 and three Society of Business Editors and Writers Awards.

In 2001, [[Out (magazine)|''Out'' magazine]] named Morrow one of the year's 100 most successful [[gay]] people in the United States. He became the first Reynolds Endowed Chair of Business Journalism at the [[University of Nevada, Reno|University of Nevada]] in [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]], [[Nevada]], where he taught from August 2009 until his death on February 1, 2010. Morrow died of [[pancreatic cancer]].

