{{Sweden-business-bio-stub}}

'''Gesetz über Kapitalanlagegesellschaften''' '''([[KAGG]])''' &mdash; ([[German language|German]] for '''Investment Company Act''') &mdash; was a set of German regulations for Mutual Funds that was phased out in 2007 and replaced by the German Investment Modernization Act ("Investement Act"). An objective of the new Investment Act is to promote Germany as an investment fund market, stemming the erstwhile exodus of German-managed funds that became domiciled in other European havens,<ref>[[François-Serge Lhabitant]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=3ZWICLVortMC&pg=PA129&lpg=PA129&dq=%22german+investment+companies+act%22&source=bl&ots=GzE83tMeuS&sig=cuyF5UvhgnUiHIVLkgDCe_RH9Ko&hl=en&ei=EytDTZ2dAoX6lwfl0p0q&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=10&ved=0CE4Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=%22german%20investment%20companies%20act%22&f=false ''Handbook of Hedge Funds'', pg. 129] [[John Wiley & Sons]] (2006)</ref> namely [[Luxembourg]]. [[BaFin]] is the regulatory enforcement agency that oversees the German financial industry.
== References == '''Citations''' * CFS Working Paper No. 2003/14 [http://ideas.repec.org/p/cfs/cfswop/wp200314.html ''Institutional Investors in Germany: Insurance Companies and Investment Funds]'' by Raimond Maurer '''Inline citations''' {{reflist}}
